observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Adapt and maintain the asset method of recording the inventory items and require the coordination between the Municipal Accountant and the designated GSO towards the proper implementation of the perpetual inventory method of recording all inventory items adopting the procedures in the MNGAS for LGUs to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies and materials;
Determine whether the reported balances, which remained non-moving from beginning to end, are actually on hand and existing and do the necessary corrections in the books;
Require department heads/ end-users accountable for inventories to maintain stock cards for all stocks and regularly update, monitor, balance and reconcile the stock cards against stocks on hand; and
Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer to conduct an urgent inventory of welfare goods to identify items nearing spoilage and report its status to proper local officials for possible drafting and implementation of an ordinance governing the distribution of welfare goods including guidelines on the frequency of distribution, prioritization criteria, and allocation mechanisms to target individuals and families in need.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to ensure that:
The Municipal Accountant:
Present the current portion of Loans Payable account under Financial/ Current Liabilities in the SFPo, and disclose its details in the NFS in keeping with IPSAS 1. As a support thereof, to submit a separate and updated Schedule of Loan Amortization as basis for the Finance Committee in the preparation of the LGU’s Annual Budget and for the Accounting Office to make the necessary adjustments of the recorded loan amortizations, to show the correct amounts actually paid for the principal and the loan interest;
Analyze and identify all possible causes of variances between book balance and the Bank’s confirmed balance;
Reconcile variances with the Bank and make necessary adjustments in the books to present the actual outstandings loan balance as of year-end; and
Ensure that the amount presented in the SFPo matches the details presented in the NFS.
The LFC:
Maintain special accounts for every loan obtained using the proper account codes as prescribed presently in the RCA for LGUs and SLs under COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;
Ensure that all loan related transactions and documents are properly kept and maintained;
Obtain bank confirmation balances as deemed necessary to facilitate reliable reconciliation; and
Install stringent internal controls in the record-keeping, payment and the recording of the Loans Payable – Domestic account to ensure accuracy of the account.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to ensure that the LOs and MT to maintain the cashbooks accordingly by adopting the following suggested measures:
Update the cashbook daily based on the Report of Collections and Deposits submitted by the Collectors;
Closely monitor and ensure the accuracy and physical existence of cash on hand by reconciling daily the cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook;
Reconcile the cashbook balance with the accounting records every end of the quarter; and
Reflect the necessary corrections in the books requiring adjustments to reconcile both the cashbook and the SL.

We recommended, and the Management, through the Municipal Engineer, agreed that:
At the beginning of each year, the Management will provide the Office of the Auditor with a comprehensive inventory of all active PPAs as well as those that are scheduled for implementation throughout the year;
Submit to COA the monthly monitoring report on the implementation of the PPAs using the template prescribed in the above-mentioned circular;
Upload and post the monthly monitoring report in the LGU’s website or LGU’s bulletin boards as part of its Transparency Seal; and
At every project site, the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices  be installed to apprise the public of project details.

a) Submit lists/details of the recorded settlement of various accountable officials in the reconciling items as to how it was settled for COA verification and issuance of NSSDC if warranted;
b) Review records and evaluate the reconciling items and prepare the appropriate adjusting entries in coordination with the audit team;
c) Coordinate with accountable officials identified in the unsettled Notice of Suspension (NS) amounting to ₱16,229.65 to submit required documents, otherwise ND will be issued; and
d) Enforce collections/settlement of the issued NDs with the corresponding NFD and SN issued and coordinate with the audit team for issuance of NSSDC if warranted.

We recommended and the management agreed to require the Inventory Committee:

To conduct an inventory of all PPE accounts once every year and COA must be invited as an observer; 

To observe the procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 pertaining to missing/non-existing property by identifying the officers/personnel who are accountable for these properties and demand the production of the same;

The disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs should be strictly implemented in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

Request from COA an authority to derecognize the unaccountable missing PPE from the books of accounts after an investigation in accordance with Paragraph 8 of this Circular.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct a risk assessment; 
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to mitigate the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit a plan to the MDRRMO for review,  to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommend that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

2.7. We recommended and management agreed that:

a. The Municipal Accounting Office to prepare the necessary entries to set up the liability account for the 15 per cent and 5 per cent collections from building fees and other charges;

b. The Municipal Treasury Office and Municipal Accounting Office prepare a separate account for the 15 per cent share of building permit fees and other charges and maintain a separate Trust Fund or Trust Liability account;

c. The Building Official shall prepare a Program of Work detailing the manner of utilization of the 15 per cent share to be held under trust, to be approved by the Local Chief Executive, and to be submitted to the DPWH Secretary thru the NCBDO;

d. The Municipal Treasury Office to remit the 5 per cent DPWH Share.

e. Henceforth, comply with the provisions of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1096 and DILG and DPWH Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 001 relative to the accounting and remittance of building permit fee collections.

Recommendations
We reiterated our recommendations and the Management agreed to require the:
Municipal Assessor to provide a copy of an updated Assessment Roll to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to Article 339 of the IRR of Republic Act (RA) 7160 which states that the Municipal Assessor shall submit an assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed and the values of such properties to the Municipal Treasurer concerned on or before the 31st day of December each year;
Municipal Treasurer to:
Prepare a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which data should come from the RPTAR/Taxpayer's Index Card maintained at the Municipal Treasurer's Office;
Furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the certified list to serve as a basis for recording the Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable accounts in the books;
Municipal Accountant to:
Record the receivables based on the list furnished by the Municipal Treasurer to recognize in the books accurate and verifiable data pursuant to Section 20, Chapter 3 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs Volume I; and
Reconcile recorded RPT/ SET transactions and make necessary correcting/ adjusting entries.

We recommended and the management agreed that the LCE requires the concerned departments to:

Stop the procurement of high-end and expensive equipment especially if the required output of that office could be done by equipment that is much more affordable and with passable quality;

Submit a justification as to the necessity of the equipment purchased. Please cite the features of that equipment where the output of the department could greatly be affected if that certain feature is absent;

Be prudent in the purchase of equipment, taking into consideration the cost and the necessity in the performance of their duties and responsibilities.

